The paper deals with probabilistic models for learning user preferences from social media data, which is a common topic in the subfield of social media analysis (cs.SI). The proposed model incorporates limited attention, which is a psychological factor, and thus the paper could also be categorized under human-computer interaction (cs.HC). The model uses collaborative topic regression, which is a machine learning technique commonly used in natural language processing and information retrieval (cs.IR). The paper also evaluates the model's performance in predicting held-out votes on news items, which is a task related to social network analysis (cs.SOC). Finally, the paper compares the proposed model with state-of-the-art models, which is a common practice in machine learning research (cs.LG).
